Deverus 2025-04-04 10:25 p.m.
im going to do it anyways. i have a wife to get to bed with.

in reviewing the contents of the affidavit, i'm seeing nothing that would fall in-line with the requirements outlined in rule 2 of the mayflower rules of criminal procedure, particularly where such rule requires "cases in which exigent circumstances exist" such as where "the person has left the immediate presence of law enforcement officers...who have probable cause"

while the same rule goes on to say that arrest warrants may also be filed in connection with a criminal information, the filing agency, specifically the mayflower national guard, made no such filing.

all that being said, the err here is twofold: firstly on the national guard, specifically the judge advocate general's corps for signing the arrest warrant to begin with. secondly, the court in approving such a warrant whereas the warrant evidently does not rise to the burden required by its very own rules.

to forego the existing, well-founded rule requiring exigent circumstances, i.e. LTAA to be present to file an arrest warrant and instead require an information to be filed with every arrest warrant is not only a radical change in how the court functions, but will also have substantial impacts on the economy of this court, and place an undue burden on an already stretched judiciary.

the attorney general will be on later to address other matters, up to and including whether or not the justice department will pursue charges against mr.arireclaimer in connection with this matter. however, as his representative for the time being, i would like to make it evident that it is the opinion of the justice department that to promulgate such a rule as detailed above is respectfully nonsensical and entirely unecessary.

good night gentlemen.

walter! 2025-04-04 11:17 p.m.
The imposition of court-backed criminal penalties beyond the due process afforded in a trial is certainly troubling. As a matter of fact, being arrested carries significant weight on your ability to do just about anything in this group. Entire careers, even, have been destroyed based on the actions of a peace officer. This is not to say that we should not give weight to these arrestsrather, that we must act carefully with how they are imposed. It is for this reason that our habeas corpus procedures do not serve, primarily, to release would-be defendants from custody. Instead, they serve the primary purpose or allowing for an after-the-fact trial.

When a courtthis Courtissues a warrant, they fundamentally assign criminal guilt to the would-be defendant. While sure, that would-be defendant could move to quash the warrant, or could challenge it after the fact using the habeas corpus procedures, the assignment of criminal guilt by the Court finding probable cause (the standard we have assigned as the minimum to have career impacts and gameplay impacts) may potentially violate a would-be defendant's rights in criminal matters.

These warrants are not orders to appear, they are orders to arrest and charge. Because of that, they are used by malintentioned law enforcement to pursue their 'enemies,' and where members of the courts and the Legislature are also members of our police departments, they become a tool for political prosecution without having the need to bring forth any formal criminal charges, prove actual guilt, or the ability to mount a defense.

It is clear to me that, on these grounds alone, these 'arrest and charge' warrants should not even exist. Warrants which compel attendance via arrest are surely appropriate and applicably within the Court's proper poweras it must compel those persons to appear before them, to answer for certain offenses or otherwise. Warrants which serve outside of that purpose should not be granted.

I would also like to point out that the prosecutorial discretion exercised by the Attorney General (the office thereof, not the person) is supreme in all matters before charges are docketed before this court. This is a fundamental portion of the separation of powers doctrine. In fact, for the Court to compel the Attorney General to pursue charges which he has not docketed represents a major overreach of judicial authority into the affairs of the executive branch, and threatens to jeopardize the impartiality of the judiciary. As the warrant itself represents no docketing of criminal charges, it cannot possibly be that the court shouldor even has the authority tocompel the Attorney General to pursue those matters.
